metadata.description:
This project is part of a larger experiment that explores and celebrates the process of making generative art by progressively releasing iterations, working towards a final release on my main account (tz1RkYY3jr1ocuPdQqrRefr5FqoawKQsmBmD). The iterations will be titled ____ 0.1, ____ 0.2, etc. At this point, the number of iterations has not been determined, but more information will be provided as this experiment unfolds.

The final release will only be made available to those who have collected each iteration (using an allowlist), and will be released for free.

metadata.name: Garden Of Symmetry #128
metadata.description:
Sometimes, things look better when seen from the distance. Not from far away, but from a length that allows one to see what’s possibly underneath. Or, you may not see anything. Instead, you can just enjoy things falling into place.

Get a pack of shattered glass, snow, or ice*, uncovering a pattern. Or an axis of dancing geometries. Enter the Garden of Symmetry.

The graphic is a plottable SVG file in A3 format, ready to be drawn using a pen plotter. In the full screen view, click somewhere on the artwork to download a copy.

I recommend to optimize the SVG before plotting, i.e. using vpype. I also recommend to draw the graphic using 0.7mm pen.

metadata.name: life is a (beautiful) mess #71
metadata.description:
when carefully applied, chaos brings things to life.

'life is a (beautiful) mess' was created as i led a certain amount of chaos take control of an animated textile algorithm i'm developing. 
as soon as it happened i realized that it was a great representation of our lives. 
each line represents one of us and the patterns that appear repeatedly are the situations we live which make us move, feel and be in a certain way. 
the image created is the sum of our paths in this life, as they only make sense when we look at them as one.

---

i hope you find it pleasant to watch this animation, how it develops and grows during aprox 1'30"
there are pieces drawn with the 4 typical school pen colors: black, green, blue and red. also a multicolor and a rare dark mode features.


press [s] to capture an image .png
press [r] to reload the animation
click the mouse to stop the animation
doubleclick the mouse to resume the animation

generative art created by mehno using p5js

metadata.name: Ethereal Microcosm #262
metadata.description:
An exploration of algorithmic organisms in a contained environment.

This piece is about the simulation of microscopic patterns using a high number of even tinier agents all following the same rules. Different species evolve and interact together, resulting in stabilizing patterns out of their parametric configurations. A form of artificial life.

This work is based on the paper "Characteristics of pattern formation and evolution in approximations of physarum transport networks", written by Jeff Jones and popularized in the artistic field by Sage Jenson. Some features were added to increase the visual and behavioral complexity of the system. Agents are divided into different species, with their own set of rules and interacting with their own substrate. Substrates also interact with each other and agents will mutate in contact of some of them.

NFT License
Runs properly on Chrome 97.0.4692.99
GPU intensive

Press P to pause (double tab touch devices)

metadata.name: Artifact #143
metadata.description:
This project is about uncovering artifacts.

Each piece is determined by approximately 15 parameters. This allows for a multitude of possible forms, and each iteration is an artifact to be discovered within the multidimensional space.

This work is focused around discovery. It is about exploring the space of the algorithm, shedding light on its many forms, and sometimes finding artifacts of the real world embedded within them.

Technically, this work is a composition of three primary elements: Voronoi tessellations, orthographic projection, and the depth-sort algorithm.
The latter of these is integral to the rendering mechanism. It works intuitively, drawing distant objects before near objects, evaluating the distance of each object according to its geometric center. It does this precisely, and in doing so, it can produce interesting visual artifacts, drawing some shapes in an unexpected order.



This has been a fascinating study, bringing light to unreal shapes and forms, and uncovering artifacts in an impossible space.

I hope you enjoy it,
Nat Sarkissian





Technical Notes:
- Append “&mag=N” to the end of the URL in live mode to specify a resolution multiplier. It will render the image N times larger than the size of your window. If you have specified anything greater than 1, a download will start automatically once the rendering is done.

metadata.name: Daydreamer #39
metadata.description:
‘For the artist communication with nature remains the most essential condition. The artist is human, himself nature; part of nature within natural space.’ (Paul Klee, 1944) 


Working on long-form nature has an interesting side effect. On the one hand, you're attempting a shallow imitation of a landscape.... You are working with cold logic and code, vainly trying to control randomness to create this virtual facsimile, something you know is artificial.... 

....and yet.... even with all this left-brain activity, your right-brain pushes back, and imagines being there. While working on this project I found myself continually daydreaming, wandering off to hear the sounds of waterfalls, or the crunch of walking along a sandy lake shore. If you've ever wondered about coding, I urge you to learn. Daydreams await....


Press '1' once rendering is finished, to redraw at 5120x5120 resolution 
Press '2' to export without post-processing effects 

3rd party libraries (license text and links included in source) 
- p5.js - Creative coding framework 
- JS Topology Suite "JSTS", a port of Java Topology Suite "JTS" - High-level Geometry library 
- WebGLImageFilter, Dominic Szablewski - phoboslab.org 

I have tried to use soft blurs and shadows to give a sense of layering and depth to the scene. After viewing for a while, it reminds me of 3D paper-art. There are traits for colour and amount of birds, waterfalls, etc. but none are especially rare – These properties are intended for filtering the collection.

metadata.name: Boom_fx_max #80
metadata.description:
Boom_fx_max, by Stephen Boyd  
August, 2022  
Little India, Toronto, Canada.

This is a free mint for anyone who is a holder of Boom_fx as of August 31, 2022, 00:11:00Z. 

Signed 18" x 12" or 12" x 12" prints are available to holders for both Boom_fx and Boom_fx_max tokens on request. Please send a DM for more information.

Any unclaimed reserves will be released after four days and available at a price to be determined. 


Project Description
---
Boom_fx_max uses all eleven days of data in one image. This constitutes 4,567 earthquakes being represented in every output. This differs from the original Boom_fx which used hours of time on one of the eleven days and typically included a few hundred seismic events.

There are eleven new colour palettes and seven different ratios to organize relationships between visual elements.

The earthquake data comes from the USGS API. There is further documentation (./documentation/Information_about_boom_fx_max.md) included with this project that outlines how this data was collected and the information included in these feeds.


Three Features
---
1. Aspect ratios:
   - Landscape
   - Portrait
   - Square
2. Eleven colour palettes
3. Seven Organizing Principle Ratios:
   - Super Golden Ratio
   - PHI
   - Golden Angle
   - Silver Ratio
   - Euler's Number
   - Reciprocal Fibonacci Constant
   - Feigenbaum Constant


Interaction
---
Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press t: thumbnail @ a maximum pixel width or height of 200px
- Press s: your current screen size
- Press p: print size @ a maximum pixel width or height of 4800px which is 16"@300dpi
- Press h: HD4K on the vertical @ a maximum pixel width or height of 2160px
- Press m: Max size @ a maximum pixel width or height of 10800px.

The filename will include some metadata such as the unique hash, date and time at time of capture.


Appreciation
---
Thank you to everyone who has collected one my pieces.

Thank you to the USGS for making this data available.

And thank you the most to KIRH.


Data Sources, Software Libraries and VCS / Source Code
--- 
Data Sources
All earthquake data is sourced from the USGS Earthquake API for the International Federation of Digital Seismograph Networks (FDSN). 

Software Libraries Used
Made with Processing / P5.js  
p5.js v1.4.1 February 02, 2022

metadata.name: Holy Mountain #89
metadata.description:
Mountains throughout human history have taken on deep meanings. Coated with immense sacredness by all peoples in the most different places. Being them as a representation of God himself or being the object of worship. For many the mountains were the very abode of the Gods. They are in the collective unconscious as the ability to connect men and gods, through the flow of energy between earth and heaven.

The symbology is very strong. It unconsciously reminds us of the process of encounter between the loneliness of the earth and the hope of the sky, between the fog that blinds and the cloud that supports, between the abyss of the ground and the proximity of the stars. All this is very charming and fascinating.

All human beings have their own mountain, which demands from each one their limits to reach the top, the desire for the breathtaking view, the fear of falling, but also the hope of the last step at the highest point.

In generative art it couldn't be different, going through all the learning, from its fundamentals, to all the countless hours of tests, to countless moments of problem solving and research and more research. This whole process is without a doubt like climbing a mountain. Thinking about the project is exactly like looking at a mountain and imagining how exhausting it will be all the way to conquer it. Finishing your work is like breathing a sigh of relief, looking down and seeing how hard it was to get there, but at the same time looking ahead and realizing how rewarding it was to be able to have that vision and breathe the refreshing breeze of the moment.

After going through a transformation in my first work, where I transmuted my artistic essence from illustration to generative art. Now I come to this second work that I delved into, and after months of climbing this mountain of mine, I give it to you.


- Press "S" in live view mode after loading to save at 1600x1600px.

metadata.name: The Climb #175
metadata.description:
The climb is about the search for purpose.

Everyone needs a purpose, a path that leads somewhere. Whether you reach it or not is not the point, it’s about the climb. The search for a purpose gives our life meaning. It gives us a reason to look for something more.

Unfortunately, there is no universal truth as to what your purpose in life is. Everyone is unique. Different. We are the product of our upbringing, environment and the cumulative sum of thousands of microdecisions. We need to find meaning for ourselves. Our unique meaning. On this path, we climb alone.

“The Climb” is created to be raw, unique, beautiful and violently volatile, much like our lives.


Everything is written in javascript and p5js.
It can sometimes take a little while to render on older computers.

metadata.name: The Living Book #2 Moonrise #47
metadata.description:
I have been exploring the medium of print for years. Mixing etching, silk-screening, offset, photocopy, risography, drawing and painting to design and craft experimental art books.From the day digital, which had always fascinated me, took over my publishing practice, I always liked to create bridges between these two worlds.

The Living Books is part of this series of hybrid and experimental works where paper and digital resonate.

This issue #2 is made of 64 pages that will be minted by collectors. A book will eventually be printed and the pages will follow the mint order. Each page exists in a cover version (c) and a xerox version (x).

Controls :

• Click to dive into each frame.
• Press C to toggle cover mode.
• Press X to toggle xerox mode.
• Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

———————

The Living Book #2 Moonrise by Ferdinand Dervieux, 2022
Made with Unity
